##The Fed's bombshell is fueling fears that only a vaccine can save global financial markets

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

-- Ai Jingwei

On the evening of March 16th, global financial markets were again in a state of panic, despite bans on short selling and interest rate cuts by central banks. On the evening of March 13th, the markets were still buzzing with excitement, but a weekend passed and suddenly the bears were back.

By 9:30 p.m. on March 16, the S & P 500 was down 8.14% and the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 9.71% , triggering another circuit breaker, with early European markets plunging and South African shares down more than 12% , their biggest ever drop. Buffett's 89 year old life has seen a lot of young people this week.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Let's start with a-share investors on the morning of March 16th, which should be a bit of a shock. How come there isn't a retaliatory rebound? Why did the Central Bank's 550-billion-yuan targeted downgrade come on top of a 9.29% jump in the S & P 500 on Friday night?

The Fed should take the blame for this, once and for all. It turns out that the Federal Reserve cut interest rates sharply on March 15th, slashing the target range for the federal funds rate to 0-0.25% and announcing a $700 billion program of quantitative easing (QE) , that includes buying back $500bn of treasuries and adding $200bn of mortgage-backed securities.

It was the Fed's latest emergency move, following an emergency 50 basis point cut in interest rates on March 3. It is worth noting that this is another early move, originally scheduled for a meeting on March 18, but now ahead of the king bomb.

The timing of the Fed's move is understandable from a policy standpoint, as trump reversed course on Friday and began issuing a series of policy responses to the outbreak. That was one reason for Friday's retaliatory rally.

But from the market's point of view, the Fed is shooting itself in the foot. Markets were likely to calm themselves and reduce volatility after Friday's retaliatory rally. But the Fed's sudden sell off, especially to zero interest rates, coupled with its extraordinary $700bn of Qe, means that the future of policy space is limited and it is time to start streaking.

Zero interest rates and Qe, the actions of the Federal Reserve at the height of the financial crisis in 2008, have been thrown into the mix in the face of an epidemic that will only exacerbate the panic?

As a result of the Fed sell-off, S & P 500 futures plunged less than half an hour into early morning trading on March 16, then fell 4.79 per cent and hit circuit breakers.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
With U.S. stock futures again fusing, asset prices are being affected, and even gold and silver are falling, with silver below $13 an ounce, the lowest price since 2009 and even lower than the cost of mining. Oil, which collapsed last week, has collapsed even further, with Brent prices falling below $32.

Panic broke out as the share price of Britain's ABF was suspended on March 16th after an oolong index suddenly fell from 1,559p to 0.01 P 100p, that's an outrageous amount of money for a company with a market value of one billion to be bought for less than 80,000 pounds.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
As for the a-share market, though, economic data for January and February, released at National Bureau of Statistics of the People's Republic of China on March 16th, show the impact of the epidemic. For example, in January and February, the value added of industries above the scale dropped by 13.5 percent year-on-year; the total volume of retail sales of consumer goods was 5,213 billion yuan, down by 20.5 percent year-on-year; and fixed asset investment (excluding rural households) nationwide was 3,332.3 billion yuan, down by 24.5 percent year-on-year. But it was mostly predictable, even better than expected.

In addition, on March 13, the central bank announced a 550 billion yuan cut, a deliberate attempt to hedge the economic data released on the morning of March 16. But even so, was the Fed backfired Wang Bang policy to bring down the ditch.

Investment capital is based on the two basic dimensions of facts and data, but the game of investment is played in the third dimension of emotions and the fourth dimension of dreams. For the current financial market, has entered a stage of panic, the market psychology is also very subtle.

Since the second half of last week, major central banks around the world have joined forces to inject liquidity as central banks in the UK have followed through with interest rate cuts, but monetary easing has not saved lives relative to the panic of the epidemic. In fact, for the global financial markets now, the most confidence is the vaccine!

The writer is a senior Marketer and author of the Leveraged Black Hole
